2. Read continuous logs & count INFO/ERROR/WARN occurrences

Answer:
Use streaming approach (BufferedReader) to process line-by-line.
Avoid loading full file into memory.
Use a counter map for log levels.
Example:

Map<String, Integer> count = new HashMap<>();
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("app.log"));
String line;
while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
    if (line.contains("INFO")) count.merge("INFO",1,Integer::sum);
    if (line.contains("ERROR")) count.merge("ERROR",1,Integer::sum);
    if (line.contains("WARN")) count.merge("WARN",1,Integer::sum);
}
3. Loyalty, Wallet, Bank payments – Monolithic vs Microservices
Monolithic approach

Answer:
Single application handles all payment types.
Uses single DB transaction (ACID).
Easy consistency but tightly coupled.
Example: One transaction updates wallet + loyalty + bank payment together.

Microservices approach

Answer:
Each payment type is a separate service.
Use Saga pattern for distributed transactions.
Event-driven communication (Kafka).
Ensure eventual consistency.
Example: Order service → Wallet service → Bank service via events.

How transactions are handled?

Answer:
Use Saga (orchestration/choreography) instead of 2PC.
Each service performs local transaction + emits event.
If failure occurs → trigger compensation.
Ensure idempotency and retries.
Example: Wallet deducted → bank fails → refund wallet via compensation event.
